\section{\texttt{\textbf{move{\_}base}}}

The \texttt{move{\_}base} package \cite{moveBasePaper} is the most important part of the ROS navigation stack and is used for path planning, both for local planning and global planning, and their execution. The \texttt{move{\_}base} package receives goal poses as input and calculates velocity commands for the robot to reach the goal. In Figure \ref{move_base} an overview over the \texttt{move{\_}base} package architecture is given.

\begin{figure}[h]
  \includegraphics[width=1.02\textwidth]{figures/move_base.pdf}
  \caption[\texttt{move{\_}base} architecture]{\texttt{move{\_}base} architecture (source: \url{http://wiki.ros.org/move\_base})}
  \label{move_base} 
\end{figure}

The modular architecture is beneficial as each component can be chosen separately to fit the robot and the task. The planning problem is split into two parts, the global planning and the local planning. The \texttt{global{\_}planner} receives the goal pose and plans a path from the current robot location to the goal. For the generation of valid paths a costmap of the environment is necessary. A costmap is a grid map, where each cell contains information about how much the planner should avoid the cell. Cells containing obstacles have very high costs and the cost decreases with increasing distance to an obstacle. The costmap used by the \texttt{global{\_}planner} is usually based on a map of the environment and additional information from sensors. The \texttt{local{\_}planner} receives the path generated by the \texttt{global{\_}planner} and generates velocity commands to follow this path. To avoid collisions the \texttt{local{\_}planner} has a costmap of the local neighborhood, which is generated from incoming sensor data. If either the \texttt{global{\_}planner} fails to generate a valid path or the \texttt{local{\_}planner} fails to generate valid velocity commands, recovery behaviors are executed. These involve the clearance of the costmaps and, if possible, in-place rotations. If the recovery behaviors do not solve the problem, the navigation is aborted. 